The locust years of Latin America
Bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is fraying, and political instability is growing.
It's hardly surprising since most countries in Latin America have spent the past twenty years going nowhere.
Capitals have been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been eaten by locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual GDP growth rate per capita in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in global trade except through still timid wage increases?
The economic stagnation is the responsibility of a bad government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and very widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush towards privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been sold off.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues generated by privatization have produced little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing by domestic buyers exhausted all available credit channels.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The influx of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would engage in another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that functioned on technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being questioned, and a random and even more corrupt effort at redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more luck; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who are leading in opinion polls in the period leading up to the Brazilian presidential elections, suggests that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic thinking and politics that capital has already started to flee - even though the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but it may prove to be ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about Mexico's emerging democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team that knows what it's doing.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economically speaking financial result because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little foundation to accumulate capital and increase productivity.
Venezuela now laments the fat years of the 1970s OPEC -- to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
Argentina's wealth is now taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps permanently.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed instead of saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates almost reach 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
The government institutions are pro-market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
The rewards for taking risk and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
It cannot be denied that China remains a poor country.
Its GDP per capita represents only half that of Brazil.
But with growth in China's coastal region of around 15% per year, which can seriously question whether in the next 15 years it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to go smoothly, first due to the massive influx of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of WTO membership.
In Latin America, things continue to deteriorate: governments are backtracking on reform and the economy is losing ground to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely behind us.
We should therefore expect even worse economic, social, and political news in the coming years.
The demagogues like Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may seem like a bad joke, but anyone concerned about Latin America's fate should not laugh at them.
